<br>
I think it's a mistake to argue that something like a hunger strike in a completely different context should be seen as belittling the likes of Gandhi.  Gandhi's greatness, as I say, was not derived from individual actions such as a hunger strike.  His greatness came from his dedication to a just cause, and relentless pursuit of that cause through non-violent means.  The actual means used, such as the hunger strike, are secondary, and to think Blaine's stunt diminishes Gandhi's achievements would be to show a remarkable shallowness of thought. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub228.ezboard.com/bxevserverboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=amanensia>Amanensia</A> at: 10/22/03 6:09 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub228.ezboard.com/bxevserverboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=usildordhujata>Usildor Dhujata</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Crypt Pimp</span><br>  Posts: 902<br> <font color=#330000>(10/22/03 7:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub228.ezboard.com/fxevserverboardsfrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1077.topic&index=38>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://members.aol.com/poeticsarcasm/images/marblemn.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Good God..</span><hr size=1> Blame artists or entertainers who do stunts and events just for ratings and money and NOT for political change?  Wow, I guess painters, actors, singers, sculpters, magicians, acrobats and lots of other types must have it hard in London.  It would really suck to have food thrown at you while trying to paint.  But damn them for trying to get attention with their work!  They even paint outside sometimes where people can see and then even have the audacity to put them up on walls and want people to come pay to see them.  Damn them straight to hell!  Hey England, get laid already and loosen the fuck up.  <br>
